      "seed": 532049224,
      "version": 22611,
      "versionNonce": 1320591788,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1769108272254,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "FRs:\n\nAll configuration changes are versioned, validated, and rolled out asynchronously; all control actions are audited and permission-restricted. The platform must emit structured, auditable signals\nfor training execution and inference activity, sufficient to support downstream analytics, monitoring, and future evaluation workflows.\n\n 1. Model Development & Training\n    Configure Batch Training Jobs ( Schedule / Algorithm / Dataset / Scale / Tenant )\n    Observe Testing and Validation Correctness\n    Observe Resource usage and Cost\n    Control Pause / Resume / Cancel / Disable / Start per configured Job\n 2. Model Registry & Lifecycle\n    Configure version registration and metadata\n    Configure Promotion Targets(Dev -> Staging -> Prod)\n    Observe Models versions in both dev and prod\n    Release status and lifecycle history\n    Control Promote, Rollback, and Delete of a Model Version\n 3. Model Serving (Online Inference)\n    Model-to-tenant and environment mapping\n    Traffic Routing and Scaling\n    Configure Event Integration\n    Observe Inference Health, Latency, and Errors\n    Observe Budget and gating\n    Observability(metric and logs)\n    Control Inference( Deploy, Delete, Revert ) per Tenant and Environment\n 4. Evaluation & Approval Workflow\n    Approval groups and policies\n    Inference telemetry and analytics inputs \n    Model correctness feedback and evaluation results\n    Approve or reject model promotion\n 5.Tenant / Team Experience (what do teams do through UI/API?)\n    Resource configuration (K8s, quotas)\n    Integrate with enterprise identity and access management\n    Batch training submission\n    Model Management and Registry\n    Runtime Control (Deploy / Revert) \n    Release Approval / Reject\n    Budget Approval\n    Inference telemetry Stream\n    Inference telemetry Analytics \n    Observability ( Metrics, Alerts, and Logs )\n\nNFRs:\n Avail: DP SLO = 99.99%; CP SLO = 99.99%; rejected traffic due to quota/budget enforcement excluded from SLO.\n Latency: inference p95/p99 ≤ 3s / 30s measured end-to-end; cold-start latency included.\n Scale: peak 20k RPS; 100 tenants; ~1k models; payloads ≤100 KB.\n Security: strong authN/Z; per-tenant isolation; encryption in transit/at rest; immutable audit retention 3y.\n Cost: per-tenant GPU budgets; global overload protection via admission control; chargeback at 5-minute granularity.\n Operability: SLOs via golden signals + burn rate; auto rollback ≤10m, manual ≤30m; paging aligned to ownership.\n Resilience/DR: 2 async regions; DP RPO <1m / RTO <30m; CP RPO <5m / RTO <60m.\n\nExplicit Scope Declaration & Named Invariants:\n1) In Scope(V1):\n    Control Plane( Resource configuration, Batch training submission, Model Management and Registry, Runtime Control (Deploy / Revert),  Release Approval / Reject, Budget Approval ) Note:\nBatch training submission refers to orchestration and lifecycle control only; data sourcing and feature engineering are explicitly out of scope.\n    Integrate with enterprise identity and access management\n    Policy Enforcement\n    Rate Limiting\n    Observability ( Metrics, Alerts, and Logs )\n    Inference telemetry emission \n2) Out of Scope:\n    Inference Telemetry consumption\n    Analytics \n    Training Data\n    Experimentation Routing\n3) Named Invariants\n    Immutable Promotion History: All model versions and configuration changes must be recorded immutably and be replay-able to a known-good state for audit and rollback.\n    Explicit Promotion Gate: No model version may serve inference traffic in an environment without explicit approval and promotion through the control plane.\n    Derived-Decision Cache Only: Data plane authorization/budget decisions are derived from control-plane state; the data plane cache is never authoritative and can be safely lost/rebuilt.\n    Strict Tenant Isolation: Inference execution, resource usage, and telemetry must be isolated per tenant and must not impact other tenants.\n    Fail-Closed Budget Enforcement: When a tenant exceeds its approved budget, requests must be rejected or degraded without violating correctness or impacting other tenants.\n    Bounded Inference Execution: Inference execution must terminate or fail closed within a bounded time window.\n    Control Plane Independence: Data plane inference must continue serving admitted traffic during control-plane unavailability.\n    Deterministic Chargeback: All resource usage must be attributable to a tenant with deterministic accounting granularity.\n4) Assumptions\n    Single Cloud deployment with Async DR 2nd region: Tenants<100, Models<1,000, and Inferences<10,000\n    RPS: avg(2,000), max(20,000)\n    Data: Type(json+text), Size(avg: 10kb, max: 100kb)\n    Separate K8 Cluster for Training vs Inferences, also dev, stg, and prod for both.  \n     \nAPIs:\nI won’t enumerate every endpoint, but the API surface splits into Control Plane spec/status/breaking Glass and Data Plane\ninference/cluster/tenant/reconcile/health/state/events/config/usage(budget), with explicit rollout and audit.\n\nAuth: Service↔Service uses mTLS; User↔Service uses OIDC. Tenant identity is derived by the gateway, not client-supplied. \n\nControl Plane(async reconciled desired state): \n    TenantSpec(Engineering): create/update/delete tenant; set quotas & budgets(GPU); view tenant configuration\n    TrainingJob(Data scientists): submit/pause/cancel training job; view status & results; register resulting model artifacts\n    ModelRegistry(Everyone can view, Data scientists register): register models(stored + versioned; register model artifacts and metadata in an external model repository), list / query versions,\nview promotion status\n    Rollout(Product teams): create rollout of versioned model -> env; approval/reject, update / rollback, view rollout history\n    TenantStatus(Engineering): convergence status; applied versions, rollout history\n    Usage/Billing(Product teams): query current usage vs approved budget, query historical usage (chargeback)\n    Audit(Everyone can Query): query immutable config and approval history(filter by tenant, actor, time range); \n Data Plane:\n    Inference(Priority Product teams but everyone can query): serve requests; return admission decisions; expose latency, error, saturation\n    Health & Status(Priority Product teams but everyone can query): pod readiness/liveness; last applied model version; capacity saturation indicators\n    Telemetry Emission(Priority Product teams but everyone can query): emit inference and resource usage signals(no consumption or interpretation guarantees) \n\n\nData Model & Ownership:\nControl Plane (Authoritative)\n    Tenant (owned by Platform / Product)\n            •        identity, quotas, budgets, access groups\n            •        immutable change history\n    Training Job (owned by Data Science)\n            •        job configuration and lifecycle state\n            •        execution metadata and results\n            •        no ownership of training data itself    \n    Model Registry (owned by Data Science)\n            •        model artifact references\n            •        version metadata\n            •        promotion status\n    Rollout / Inference Environment (owned by Product)\n            •        model version → environment mapping\n            •        approval state\n            •        applied vs desired state\n    Audit Records (owned by Platform)\n            •        immutable configuration and approval events\n            •        tenant-scoped and time-partitioned\n\nData Plane (Derived / Ephemeral)\n    Authorization & Budget Cache (owned by Platform)\n            •        cached decisions derived from control plane\n            •        non-durable, safe to lose\n    Inference Telemetry (owned by Platform)\n            •        append-only execution and usage signals\n            •        no correctness dependency\n            •        consumed asynchronously\n    Observability Signals (owned by Platform)\n            •        metrics, logs, traces\n            •        durability independent of serving path\n\nFinancial Attribution\n    Chargeback Records (owned by Platform)\n            •        tenant-attributed resource usage\n            •        deterministic aggregation window\n            •        used for billing and guardrails, not admission\n",
      "fontSize": 18.810274734501824,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "FRs:\n\nAll configuration changes are versioned, validated, and rolled out asynchronously; all control actions are audited and permission-restricted. The platform must emit structured, auditable signals for training execution and inference activity, sufficient to support downstream analytics, monitoring, and future evaluation workflows.\n\n 1. Model Development & Training\n    Configure Batch Training Jobs ( Schedule / Algorithm / Dataset / Scale / Tenant )\n    Observe Testing and Validation Correctness\n    Observe Resource usage and Cost\n    Control Pause / Resume / Cancel / Disable / Start per configured Job\n 2. Model Registry & Lifecycle\n    Configure version registration and metadata\n    Configure Promotion Targets(Dev -> Staging -> Prod)\n    Observe Models versions in both dev and prod\n    Release status and lifecycle history\n    Control Promote, Rollback, and Delete of a Model Version\n 3. Model Serving (Online Inference)\n    Model-to-tenant and environment mapping\n    Traffic Routing and Scaling\n    Configure Event Integration\n    Observe Inference Health, Latency, and Errors\n    Observe Budget and gating\n    Observability(metric and logs)\n    Control Inference( Deploy, Delete, Revert ) per Tenant and Environment\n 4. Evaluation & Approval Workflow\n    Approval groups and policies\n    Inference telemetry and analytics inputs \n    Model correctness feedback and evaluation results\n    Approve or reject model promotion\n 5.Tenant / Team Experience (what do teams do through UI/API?)\n    Resource configuration (K8s, quotas)\n    Integrate with enterprise identity and access management\n    Batch training submission\n    Model Management and Registry\n    Runtime Control (Deploy / Revert) \n    Release Approval / Reject\n    Budget Approval\n    Inference telemetry Stream\n    Inference telemetry Analytics \n    Observability ( Metrics, Alerts, and Logs )\n\nNFRs:\n Avail: DP SLO = 99.99%; CP SLO = 99.99%; rejected traffic due to quota/budget enforcement excluded from SLO.\n Latency: inference p95/p99 ≤ 3s / 30s measured end-to-end; cold-start latency included.\n Scale: peak 20k RPS; 100 tenants; ~1k models; payloads ≤100 KB.\n Security: strong authN/Z; per-tenant isolation; encryption in transit/at rest; immutable audit retention 3y.\n Cost: per-tenant GPU budgets; global overload protection via admission control; chargeback at 5-minute granularity.\n Operability: SLOs via golden signals + burn rate; auto rollback ≤10m, manual ≤30m; paging aligned to ownership.\n Resilience/DR: 2 async regions; DP RPO <1m / RTO <30m; CP RPO <5m / RTO <60m.\n\nExplicit Scope Declaration & Named Invariants:\n1) In Scope(V1):\n    Control Plane( Resource configuration, Batch training submission, Model Management and Registry, Runtime Control (Deploy / Revert),  Release Approval / Reject, Budget Approval ) Note: Batch training submission refers to orchestration and lifecycle control only; data sourcing and feature engineering are explicitly out of scope.\n    Integrate with enterprise identity and access management\n    Policy Enforcement\n    Rate Limiting\n    Observability ( Metrics, Alerts, and Logs )\n    Inference telemetry emission \n2) Out of Scope:\n    Inference Telemetry consumption\n    Analytics \n    Training Data\n    Experimentation Routing\n3) Named Invariants\n    Immutable Promotion History: All model versions and configuration changes must be recorded immutably and be replay-able to a known-good state for audit and rollback.\n    Explicit Promotion Gate: No model version may serve inference traffic in an environment without explicit approval and promotion through the control plane.\n    Derived-Decision Cache Only: Data plane authorization/budget decisions are derived from control-plane state; the data plane cache is never authoritative and can be safely lost/rebuilt.\n    Strict Tenant Isolation: Inference execution, resource usage, and telemetry must be isolated per tenant and must not impact other tenants.\n    Fail-Closed Budget Enforcement: When a tenant exceeds its approved budget, requests must be rejected or degraded without violating correctness or impacting other tenants.\n    Bounded Inference Execution: Inference execution must terminate or fail closed within a bounded time window.\n    Control Plane Independence: Data plane inference must continue serving admitted traffic during control-plane unavailability.\n    Deterministic Chargeback: All resource usage must be attributable to a tenant with deterministic accounting granularity.\n4) Assumptions\n    Single Cloud deployment with Async DR 2nd region: Tenants<100, Models<1,000, and Inferences<10,000\n    RPS: avg(2,000), max(20,000)\n    Data: Type(json+text), Size(avg: 10kb, max: 100kb)\n    Separate K8 Cluster for Training vs Inferences, also dev, stg, and prod for both.  \n     \nAPIs:\nI won’t enumerate every endpoint, but the API surface splits into Control Plane spec/status/breaking Glass and Data Plane inference/cluster/tenant/reconcile/health/state/events/config/usage(budget), with explicit rollout and audit.\n\nAuth: Service↔Service uses mTLS; User↔Service uses OIDC. Tenant identity is derived by the gateway, not client-supplied. \n\nControl Plane(async reconciled desired state): \n    TenantSpec(Engineering): create/update/delete tenant; set quotas & budgets(GPU); view tenant configuration\n    TrainingJob(Data scientists): submit/pause/cancel training job; view status & results; register resulting model artifacts\n    ModelRegistry(Everyone can view, Data scientists register): register models(stored + versioned; register model artifacts and metadata in an external model repository), list / query versions, view promotion status\n    Rollout(Product teams): create rollout of versioned model -> env; approval/reject, update / rollback, view rollout history\n    TenantStatus(Engineering): convergence status; applied versions, rollout history\n    Usage/Billing(Product teams): query current usage vs approved budget, query historical usage (chargeback)\n    Audit(Everyone can Query): query immutable config and approval history(filter by tenant, actor, time range); \n Data Plane:\n    Inference(Priority Product teams but everyone can query): serve requests; return admission decisions; expose latency, error, saturation\n    Health & Status(Priority Product teams but everyone can query): pod readiness/liveness; last applied model version; capacity saturation indicators\n    Telemetry Emission(Priority Product teams but everyone can query): emit inference and resource usage signals(no consumption or interpretation guarantees) \n\n\nData Model & Ownership:\nControl Plane (Authoritative)\n    Tenant (owned by Platform / Product)\n            •        identity, quotas, budgets, access groups\n            •        immutable change history\n    Training Job (owned by Data Science)\n            •        job configuration and lifecycle state\n            •        execution metadata and results\n            •        no ownership of training data itself    \n    Model Registry (owned by Data Science)\n            •        model artifact references\n            •        version metadata\n            •        promotion status\n    Rollout / Inference Environment (owned by Product)\n            •        model version → environment mapping\n            •        approval state\n            •        applied vs desired state\n    Audit Records (owned by Platform)\n            •        immutable configuration and approval events\n            •        tenant-scoped and time-partitioned\n\nData Plane (Derived / Ephemeral)\n    Authorization & Budget Cache (owned by Platform)\n            •        cached decisions derived from control plane\n            •        non-durable, safe to lose\n    Inference Telemetry (owned by Platform)\n            •        append-only execution and usage signals\n            •        no correctness dependency\n            •        consumed asynchronously\n    Observability Signals (owned by Platform)\n            •        metrics, logs, traces\n            •        durability independent of serving path\n\nFinancial Attribution\n    Chargeback Records (owned by Platform)\n            •        tenant-attributed resource usage\n            •        deterministic aggregation window\n            •        used for billing and guardrails, not admission\n",
